english:
  title: Eulogy of the Jiphyeonjeon Library Pavilion with Preface
  author: Lee Gyejeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your humble servant humbly observes that in the age of the Three Dynasties and beyond, the sage emperors and wise kings, inheriting Heaven's mandate and establishing their standards, perfected the learning of self-cultivation and governing others, exhausting fully the Way of rulership and instruction. Thus their transformative influence spread and customs grew beautiful, unmatched by later ages.

    Since then, the enlightened rulers of the two Han dynasties, Tang, and Song have devoted themselves to the Sacred Learning, establishing repositories of books within the palace—the Stone Repository and White Tiger of Han, the Hongwen and Chongwen of Tang and Song. Though the reputation for honoring this Way flourished in their time, the reality of establishing teaching through one's own conduct was nowhere to be heard.

    Heaven blesses the East, and the radiance of literary culture opens wide. Now our sovereign lord, endowed with Heaven-given sagacity and devoted to the refined learning, exalts the Confucian tradition and honors the Way. Upon ascending the throne, he established the Jiphyeonjeon and carefully selected civil ministers to staff it. He gathered extensive collections of classics and histories to support scholarly discussion. Daily he opens the Royal Lecture Hall to examine and deliberate upon antiquity and present, investigating the texts of the Six Classics and observing the precedents of a hundred dynasties. Through leisurely contemplation and deep immersion, he gathers all within his mind to respond to the infinite changes of this age, thereby perfecting the Way of rulership and instruction. Truly he alone has inherited what the sage emperors and wise kings of the Three Dynasties transmitted.

    How could those rulers of Han, Tang, and Song who merely coveted empty reputation compare even one in ten thousand times?

    Consider that the book repository had become too narrow, with volumes piled high, making consultation difficult. In the year of the Rooster, the sovereign commanded the construction of a new Jiphyeonjeon within the west gate of the palace, and built a five-bay Library Pavilion to its north. The foundation was elevated and reinforced, rising magnificent and splendid, standing like wings spread wide. Shelves were affixed to every wall, volumes arranged by category and marked with ivory tabs, making retrieval as easy as turning one's palm.

    Reverently I consider the sovereign's profound reverence for the Classics, promotion of literary governance, and stimulation of transformative education—alas, how supreme! Your servant, though of meager talent, has been privileged to stand among the worthy and to witness this flourishing of civilization. It is surely fitting that I compose this eulogy to celebrate such noble virtue. Respectfully I present this song of praise:

    ---

    The great Way eternal,
    Unchanging through the ages—
    In ancient times, emperors and kings
    Practiced it themselves, grasped it in their hearts.

    As rulers and teachers,
    Their governance shone brilliant,
    Their transformation perfected,
    Becoming the law for ten thousand generations.

    Since the Han and Tang arose,
    This Way gradually faded.
    Though some grasped at its name,
    Its substance remained unseen.

    Heaven's care turns to the East,
    Sage wisdom now ascends the throne.
    With wisdom as his resource,
    He devotes his spirit to Sacred Learning.

    The Jiphyeonjeon is established,
    Every text collected and gathered.
    Daily the Lecture Hall opens,
    And the Way and virtue are discussed.

    The source runs pure,
    The current flows clear;
    The form stands perfect,
    Its shadow falls straight.

    Great is the transformation advancing,
    Overflowing the divine grace,
    The Way of emperors passed down through ages—
    Silent for a thousand years—

    Our king rises to continue it,
    In a single dawn restored!

    Ah, magnificent fortune
    For the Eastern realm!

    The royal command has raised
    This Library Pavilion here.
    Pines grow thick, bamboos bend their grace,
    Pheasants rise and birds take flight.

    The Four Categories of books—
    Classics, histories, philosophers, and collections—
    Each in its proper place arranged,
    To find and grasp them clear as black and white.

    Oh, how great is our sovereign's
    Boon of literary learning!
    Leaving sufficiency for ages endless,
    Ten thousand generations rejoice.

    This humble servant, blessed to stand
    Among the assembly of the worthy,
    Composes now this song of praise
    To echo through eternity unending.
  footnotes:
    - The Three Dynasties refers to the semi-legendary Xia, Shang, and Zhou dynasties, representing an idealized golden age of sage-kingship in Confucian thought.
    - The Stone Repository (石渠) and White Tiger (白虎) were imperial libraries of the Han dynasty.
    - The Hongwen (弘文) and Chongwen (崇文) Halls were libraries established during Tang and Song respectively.
    - The 'Royal Lecture Hall' (經筵) was an institution where the king studied the Classics with court scholars, central to Confucian statecraft.
    - 'The Six Classics (六經) are the foundational Confucian texts: the Book of Poetry, Book of History, Book of Rites, Spring and Autumn Annals, Book of Changes, and the former two parts of the Rites of Zhou.'
    - 'The Four Categories (四部) refers to the traditional Chinese system of classifying books: Classics, Histories, Philosophers, and Collected Writings.'
    - The year of the Rooster (己酉) mentioned in the preface corresponds to 1429, during the reign of King Sejong the Great of Joseon.
